  <div class="module-content">
    <header class="module-header animate-in">
      <span class="module-number">01</span>
      <h1 class="module-title">Opening the Cookbook: Starting with an "Augmented LLM"</h1>
      <p class="module-subtitle">What the Anthropic Cookbook teaches end-to-end · And the book's minimum viable unit — the Augmented LLM</p>
    </header>

    <div class="module-body">

      <!-- Screen 1: Welcome / Hook -->
      <section class="screen animate-in">
        <h2 class="screen-heading">First question: you open ChatGPT and ask "is it raining in Shanghai today?" — what happens?</h2>
        <p>It says: "Sorry, I don't have the ability to access real-time data." At that moment, you've hit the boundary of a "bare <span class="term" data-definition="Large Language Model. Think of it as a 'text brain' trained on massive amounts of text — great at continuing conversations, but frozen at its training cutoff date. It can't browse the web, query databases, or remember what you said yesterday.">LLM</span>" — it's a talking brain trapped in a room with no windows, no phone, and no calendar.</p>
        <p><strong>The entire Anthropic Cookbook teaches you how to give this brain windows, a phone, a calendar, and a capable assistant.</strong></p>
        <div class="callout callout-accent">
          <div class="callout-icon">🧗</div>
          <div class="callout-content">
            <strong class="callout-title">This lesson's metaphor: the outdoor rock climber and their kit</strong>
            <p>A bare-handed climber can only tackle the simplest routes. Give them the four-piece kit — rope, protection cams, walkie-talkie, coach — and suddenly they can take on much harder walls. A plain LLM call is "bare-handed climbing"; the <em>Augmented LLM</em> this lesson teaches is "fully equipped climbing."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Screen 2: The four-piece kit -->
      <section class="screen animate-in">
        <h2 class="screen-heading">The Augmented LLM's "Four-Piece Kit"</h2>
        <p>In the paper <span class="term" data-definition="An engineering paper published by Anthropic in 2024 that introduces the 'Augmented LLM' as the minimum viable unit and presents 5 foundational orchestration patterns. The theoretical framework for the entire cookbook."><em>Building Effective Agents</em></span>, Anthropic engineers define the "augmented LLM" as the base unit — an LLM equipped with some subset of these four capabilities:</p>

        <div class="pattern-cards stagger-children">
          <div class="pattern-card animate-in" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-1)">
            <div class="pattern-icon" style="background: var(--color-actor-1)">🔍</div>
            <h4 class="pattern-title">Retrieval</h4>
            <p class="pattern-desc">Lets the LLM "look things up" in your own knowledge base — product docs, customer FAQs, internal wikis. The underlying mechanism is <span class="term" data-definition="Retrieval-Augmented Generation: first use keyword or vector search to find relevant document chunks, then feed those chunks into the prompt so the model can answer based on them. The most common paradigm in enterprise AI applications.">RAG</span>.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-card animate-in" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-3)">
            <div class="pattern-icon" style="background: var(--color-actor-3)">🛠️</div>
            <h4 class="pattern-title">Tools</h4>
            <p class="pattern-desc">Lets the LLM "ask someone else to do things" — check the weather, send emails, run a calculator. The LLM doesn't do the work itself; it outputs a "work ticket" that your program executes.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-card animate-in" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-4)">
            <div class="pattern-icon" style="background: var(--color-actor-4)">💾</div>
            <h4 class="pattern-title">Memory</h4>
            <p class="pattern-desc">Lets the LLM "remember what you said yesterday" — conversation history, user preferences, long-term facts. Without it, every conversation is like meeting for the first time.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-card animate-in" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-2)">
            <div class="pattern-icon" style="background: var(--color-actor-2)">📜</div>
            <h4 class="pattern-title">System Prompt</h4>
            <p class="pattern-desc">Gives the LLM a "job description" — who you are, what tone to use, which topics to avoid. Essentially "role-casts" a general-purpose trained model into your dedicated assistant.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-icon">💡</div>
          <div class="callout-content">
            <strong class="callout-title">Key Insight</strong>
            <p>All the complex patterns that come later in the cookbook (chaining, routing, orchestrator, Agent SDK, SRE auto-remediation) are ultimately just <strong>different wiring patterns between multiple Augmented LLMs</strong>. Master this minimum viable unit first, and the entire book is just different combinations of the same LEGO brick.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Screen 3: Code translation - one-liner research agent -->
      <section class="screen animate-in">
        <h2 class="screen-heading">A real code snippet: 7 lines to build a web-surfing researcher</h2>
        <p>This code comes from <code>claude_agent_sdk/00_The_one_liner_research_agent.ipynb</code> — the "Hello World" of the entire cookbook. It's the <strong>minimum viable Augmented LLM</strong>: an LLM + one tool (web search).</p>

        <div class="translation-block animate-in">
          <div class="translation-code">
            <span class="translation-label">CODE · Python</span>
<pre><code><span class="code-line"><span class="code-keyword">from</span> claude_agent_sdk <span class="code-keyword">import</span> ClaudeAgentOptions, query</span>
<span class="code-line"></span>
<span class="code-line">messages = []</span>
<span class="code-line"><span class="code-keyword">async for</span> msg <span class="code-keyword">in</span> <span class="code-function">query</span>(</span>
<span class="code-line">    <span class="code-property">prompt</span>=<span class="code-string">"Research the latest trends in AI agents and give me a brief summary and relevant citations."</span>,</span>
<span class="code-line">    <span class="code-property">options</span>=<span class="code-function">ClaudeAgentOptions</span>(<span class="code-property">model</span>=MODEL, <span class="code-property">allowed_tools</span>=[<span class="code-string">"WebSearch"</span>]),</span>
<span class="code-line">):</span>
<span class="code-line">    <span class="code-function">print_activity</span>(msg)</span>
<span class="code-line">    messages.<span class="code-function">append</span>(msg)</span></code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="translation-english">
            <span class="translation-label">Line-by-line explanation</span>
            <div class="translation-lines">
              <p class="tl"><strong>Line 1:</strong> Import the "query" function and "options" tool from Anthropic's official SDK.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>Line 3:</strong> Prepare an empty list — every message the agent sends us will be collected here.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>Line 4:</strong> Start receiving asynchronously in a stream — like watching a live broadcast; every thought and action from the agent is visible immediately.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>Line 5:</strong> Our "task order" — research the latest trends in AI agents, give me a summary and citations.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>Line 6:</strong> Key configuration — which model to use, and <strong>only</strong> allow one tool: web search. This is the "Augmented LLM": one LLM + one tool.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>Lines 8-9:</strong> Print and archive every thought, search, and response from the agent.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>The entire snippet is 7 effective lines — a researcher that can browse the web.</strong> This is the cookbook's Hello World.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

